observations.recommendation:
We reiterated our recommendation that –
 Management:
 conduct the complete annual physical count of PPE in accordance with Section 124 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Vol. 1. A representative of the Auditor be invited to witness the inventory taking for this purpose;
 see to it that a copy of the RPCPPE shall be submitted to COA for verification not later than January 31, of each year pursuant to Section 124 of the Manual on the NGAS;
 General Services Officer – Designate maintain PPE Cards and ARE/PAR and ensure that the ARE/PAR be renewed every after three years pursuant to Section 492 of GAAM, Volume 1, to establish effective management and control over PPE;
 General Services Officer-Designate and Municipal Accountant-Designate reconcile their property records with the result of physical count to ensure that PPE recorded in the property records really exists and that all existing PPE are recorded in the books, to establish correctness and completeness of balances of PPE accounts. Any variance shall be dealt accordingly and subsequently adjusted as necessary; and
 The Property and Accounting Units comply with the prescribed procedures in COA Circular No. 89-296 on the disposal of unserviceable PPE, if any.

We recommended that the -
 Municipal Engineer and the Municipal General Services Officer – Designate conduct a yearly physical count of local road network projects and accordingly update the local road map of the MLGU;
 Municipal Engineer provide the Municipal Accountant – Designate and Municipal General Services Officer – Designate the description and cost segregation of road components of various road infrastructure projects for their bases in recording in the Local Road Network Ledger Card and maintenance of Local Road Network Ledger Card, respectively;
 Municipal General Services Officer – Designate maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components; and
 The Municipal Accountant – Designate keep and maintain Local Road Network Ledger Card for roads and road components for every road network and reconcile the same with the result of the physical inventory taking at the end of the year. Also, provide for the depreciation for the local road network and disclosure in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We recommended that Management:
 Require the Municipal Accountant – Designate to draw the necessary adjusting journal entries for the various accounting errors noted in Item 5.3 to correct the balance of the Advances for Payroll account;
 Demand the former OIC Municipal Treasurer for the immediate settlement or liquidation of their respective outstanding cash advances; and
 Monitor the grant and liquidation of cash advances to avoid the accumulation of unliquidated cash advances;
 Require the Municipal Accountant-Designate to maintain subsidiary ledgers to aide in tracking and monitoring the balance of cash advances; and
 Henceforth, adhere to the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant – Designate:
 Include the PPE balances of SEF for the School Building amounting to ₱246,836.71 and Trust Fund for the Road Networks amounting to ₱9,765,556.97 in Note to FS under Note 6 - PPE;
 Make additional disclosure regarding the Loans Payable-Domestic account;
 Present comparatively the Revenues and Expenses, for more informative financial statements to the users of the report.

We recommended that Management submit the following verifiable supporting documents to enable proper evaluation and appreciation of the COVID-19 response efforts of the Municipality:
 List of recipients, showing date of receipt, quantity and goods received, corresponding barangay and signature for the distribution of relief goods worth ₱4,100,250.00;
 Lacking information per recipient of financial assistance and food allowance, as tabulated under Item 19.5.7;
 For disinfectants, medical supplies, and quarantine facilities supplies, verifiable procurement documents and distribution lists and/or Report of Supplies and Materials Issued (RSMI) supported with Requisition Issue Slip (RIS), as appropriate; and
 Photograph documentations of the COVID-19 response aid and operations of the Municipality relative to the above expenditures, properly captioned and dated.

We have recommended that Management -
submit justification for the charges made from LDRRMF despite the absence and/or sufficient appropriation thereof;
Henceforth, ensure the existence of an appropriation in accordance with Section 7 of R.A. No. 7160 and the afore-cited jurisprudence, before transactions are made or contracts are entered into by the Municipality.

We have recommended that:
Management –
create an Inventory Committee that shall perform the conduct of complete annual physical count of PPE in accordance with Section 124 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Vol. 1.  A representative of the Auditor be invited to witness the inventory taking for this purpose;
see to it that the Inventory Committee shall prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) which shall be reconciled with the PPE records kept by the of the General Services Office and Accounting Office; and that a copy of the RPCPPE shall be submitted to COA for verification not later than January 31 of each year pursuant to Section 124 of the Manual on the NGAS;
The General Services Officer maintain Property Cards for PPE and ARE/PAR and ensure that the ARE/PAR be renewed every after three years pursuant to Section 492 of GAAM, Volume 1, to establish effective management and control over PPE;
The Municipal Accountant-designate maintain complete and updated PPELC for each category of PPE pursuant to Section 114 of NGAS Manual for LGUs to provide ready information on the accounts and to support balances in the financial statements.
The General Services Officer and Municipal Accountant-designate reconcile their property records and with the result of physical count to ensure that PPE recorded in the property records really exists and all existing PPE are recorded in the books, in order to establish correctness and completeness of balances of PPE accounts. Any variance shall be handled accordingly and subsequently adjusted as necessary.
The Property and Accounting Units comply with the prescribed procedures in COA Circular No. 89-296 on the disposal of unserviceable PPE, if any.
Management Comment:
Management replied that no Municipal Inventory Committee was created and no property records were maintained. However, Management committed to create inventory committee and conduct physical inventory of PPE and to further comply for CY 2019.

We have recommended that the Municipal Accountant-designate attach and submit the:
Sanggunian Bayan Resolution authorizing the LCE to enter into such Contract of Service/Job Orders;
certified copies of Contract of Services/Job Order contracts from the Human Resource Management Officer(HRMO), along with the statement of expected work or output;
verified Accomplishment Reports and approved DTRs;
duly accomplished Obligation Request for the months of March, June to December 2018 and for the payroll of Public Relation Officer and VAWC Officer for May 2018; and
Henceforth, evaluate and ensure that disbursement vouchers are supported with complete documents before payment is effected to establish the validity of the transactions as well as the correctness of the accounts used.
Management Comment:
The Municipal Accountant – Designate submitted the Sangguniang Bayan Resolution No. 2018-01 dated January 8, 2018 authorizing the Municipal Mayor to hire Job Order employees as the need arises on August 1, 2019 along with the Job Order contracts of the employees.
Auditor’s Rejoinder:
Review of the Job Order contracts submitted disclosed that the duties and responsibilities were not specifically indicated. The Audit Team further explained that the duties and responsibilities should be indicated to facilitate evaluation vis-à-vis their accomplishment reports, whether they have met what were expected from them.

We have recommended the following:

The Municipal Treasurer, who is bonded and take custody of and exercise  proper management of funds of the Municipality, should be granted cash advances instead of the Municipal Accountant in accordance with COA Circular No. 97-002;

The ICO–Municipal Accountant to refrain from acting as disbursing officer;

The management to revisit COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 for effective and proper compliance regarding cash advances procedures.

We have recommended the following:

The Municipal Treasurer, who is bonded and take custody of and exercise  proper management of funds of the Municipality, should be granted cash advances instead of the Municipal Accountant in accordance with COA Circular No. 97-002;

The ICO–Municipal Accountant to refrain from acting as disbursing officer;

The management to revisit COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 for effective and proper compliance regarding cash advances procedures.

In view of the foregoing, we have recommended that:
 Management create an Inventory Committee that will conduct a complete annual physical count of PPE in accordance with Section 124 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Vol. 1. A representative of the Auditor be invited to witness the inventory taking for this purpose;
 the Property and Accounting Units maintain complete and accurate PPELC for each category of PPE pursuant to Section 114 on the NGAS Manual for LGUs in order to promote effective monitoring and controls over PPE;
 a reconciliation of the Property and Accounting records be done after the conduct of physical count;
 the Inventory Committee submit the Physical Inventory Reports to the Property Officer and COA Office for verification and reconciliation of the result of the physical inventory with the complete Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards and the Property Cards maintained by the Property and Accounting Units;
 ARE/PAR be maintained and renewed every three years in accordance with the Instructions on the use of ARE/PAR;

In view of the above observations, we have recommended the following:
• The Municipal Mayor creates a committee to conduct physical inventory count of the Property, Plant and Equipment to determine actual existence and condition of the properties pursuant to Section 124 of the NGAS Manual Volume 1;
• An updated and descriptive Property Card should be maintained by the Property Office;
• Likewise, the Accounting Office should maintain Property Equipment Ledger Cards as required under the NGAS to provide informative data on Property, Plant and Equipment;
• For the year 2016, the Property Officer/Municipal Treasurer should start issuing Acknowledgement Receipt of Equipment (ARE) for the particular property issued to employees to easily pinpoint accountability and facilitate inventory taking;
• The cost of the school building should be transferred to the Department of Education through a Journal Entry Voucher to be drawn by the Municipal Accountant and given to the Accountant of the DepEd.
